Turkey's diplomatic horizons are expanding
Long before Turkey began to seek accession to the European Union, European powers longed to penetrate deep into the Turkish border.
On the east bank of the Bosphorus, perhaps only twenty steps in Asia, stands one of the best monuments of this unsuccessful imperial ambition.
Hydarpa<0xC5><0xA1>a Railway Station was designed by two German architects, Otto Ritter and Helmut Conu, in a neo-Renaissance style.
The tour guide will tell you.
The building sits round the end of the platforms with towers at each corner of the front, indistinguishable from some provincial German town hall.
The stone is dirty.
The whole building is slowly falling apart.
But once a person gets inside the vaulted box office, he can no longer doubt the size of the company whose westernmost gateway to the station was.
The station was opened in August 1908 by a German consortium of the Anatolia-Baghdadi Corporation.
Germany, which was late in the game of empires, intended to realize its ambition to control the Middle East using this railroad, which was to lead to Damascus, Baghdad and further into the territory that is now Saudi Arabia.
But German imperial ambitions collapsed during the First World War.
Their tracks were attacked by Lawrence of Arabia and his irregular units.
Relative isolation from the surrounding territories, created by the frozen borders of the Cold War, is gone.
British and colonial units advanced from Egypt and expelled the Turks and their German allies from Palestine and Syria.
And there's bad news for Hydarpa<0xC5><0xA1>a station, too.
In 1917, the explosion of the ammunition train destroyed its elaborate roof.
Turkish sources say it was sabotage.
Since then, it has been gradually shrinking and history has been circumventing it.
Today, however, this gateway to Anatolia and further east serves - at least symbolically - to highlight the expanding horizons of Turkish diplomacy.
The ruling Justice and Development Party (AKP) has created a completely new foreign policy for the country.
Relative isolation from the surrounding territories, created by the frozen borders of the Cold War, is gone.
A new policy is now in place - Turkey is engaged.
It is remarkable that the Turkish government has good relations with Israel and Syria, with the Palestinian factions Hamas and Fatah, with Iraq and Iran, and of course with the European Union and the United States.
In order to review the parameters of this new policy, I boarded a night train to the Turkish capital Ankara, where I was supposed to meet with one of the leading AKP foreign policy experts, the Turkish MP Suat Kiniklioglu.
The next morning - about ten and a half hours later - after a slippery ride along the tracks reminiscent of the old-fashioned rhythms of the famous documentary Night Post, I arrived in the Turkish metropolis, designed as a new city for a secular state that wants to turn to its Ottoman past.
However, the AKP, with its well-known Islamist roots, represents a shift in the paradigm of the Turkish consensus.
Suspicion arose in the West, especially in Washington.
The taxi took me to the AKP headquarters, an ultra-modern stone and metal building deliberately built in a developing suburb, surrounded by semi-deployed department stores and power shops, where middle managers in business suits – men and women – meet to strike.
Suat Kiniklioglu could easily be a centre-right politician from almost any other European political party.
Jacket, tie, I'm sure he had a Blackberry, too.
"The aim of the party's foreign policy is to reintegrate Turkey into its immediate vicinity.
“The Cold War was an anomaly,” he said.
Turkey has been cut off from its border.
Today, we have to look east and west at the same time.
It wasn't a choice.
It must have done both.
"But there will come a time," I asked, "when may Turkey have to make a decision?"
"Turkey," he said, "you didn't want such a decision to happen."
He then underlined what almost everyone I spoke to here almost memorably said: Turkish relations not only with the Middle East, but also with the Caucasus and the Black Sea area are as good for Europe and the United States as Turkey.
With Turkey on board, it seems that Europe as a whole can, metaphorically speaking, go along these tracks to East Asia and the Middle East.
Back at Hydarpa<0xC5><0xA1>a station, after another mostly waking night, I thought of the two German gentlemen Herr Ritter and Herr Conu, who watched as this building was built a hundred years ago.
How surprised they would be if they found that European ambitions in the Middle East could now be, for the most part, in Turkish hands.
And as I waited in the harbour for the ferry back across the Bosporus, I remembered that in those days Turkey was called the "sick man of Europe".
So it seems that at least then there was not much doubt as to which continent should be entitled to this fascinating country.
