"Auto bee" prevents collisions
To make progress in the development of accident protection technologies, this time Nissan was inspired by nature, specifically bees.
This Japanese company has created a robot that takes the model of flying bees, thus preventing collisions.
This is the Bio-mimetic Car Robot Drive, or BR23C, which represents the first step in precipitation prevention technologies.
Engineers at the Center for Technological Progress Nissan Motor Co., Ltd. have developed the robot in collaboration with the Center for Advancement in Scientific and Technological Research of the prestigious Japanese University of Tokyo.
According to Kazuhiro Doi, CEO of public relations for technology, research and development of the brand, the BR23C is presented as an extension of the four zones of the Nissan safety shield.
The task of the robot is to strengthen the ability to prevent precipitation in cars of this brand.
During the flight, each bee creates its own personal oval-shaped space, which is very similar to the Nissan safety shield.
Most importantly, however, are composite bee eyes, which are able to see in all directions at an angle of more than 300 degrees, allowing the bee to fly in its personal space without stopping.
In creating this visual feature, engineers designed what they called the Laser Range Finder.
It detects obstacles up to a distance of two meters in a 180-degree radius ahead of BR23C, calculates the distance of the object and sends a signal to the on-board microprocessor, which immediately converts it to a collision warning.
"As soon as an obstacle is detected, the robot mimics the bee's movements and immediately changes direction by turning the wheels to the right or even greater angle to prevent collision.
The biggest difference from any existing system is the fact that all pernicious maneuvers are absolutely instinctive.
If that were not the case, the robot would not be able to respond quickly enough to avoid obstacles,” said Toshiyuki Andoh, director of the Mobile Lab and chief engineer of the project.
Unlike bees, the robot cannot move upwards and downwards or diagonally, its movement is limited only to two dimensions and to the direction it is allowed to rotate its wheels, but not in an infinite number of directions and possibilities as with bees.
In addition to acceleration and deceleration, Nissan also used the rotation function to prevent the robot from crashing.
"The device only needs to process the information every few seconds, and according to that data, it must be preserved.
It does not require storing information or logical intuition from previous maneuvers, so it can work without interruption with only two dozen kB of memory.
It may surprise you, but we’re not talking about giga or mega in memory.”
This is the first step in the development of new technologies for immediate precipitation prevention, a technology for which Nissan predicts the use of serial vehicles in ten years.
The robot uses lithium polymer batteries that are lighter and last longer than lithium-ion batteries.
Another possible future use of this technology could be to incorporate the unit into the GPS satellite navigation system, which would lead the driver to the destination while avoiding obstacles on the road.
