Rafael Correa on Monday in Quito.
Re-establish a republic around socialism in the 21st century.
Such is the joint project of Venezuelan Hugo Chávez, Bolivian Eva Morales and Ecuadorian Rafael Correa.
Last Sunday, the third nominee submitted to the vote, following the example of his counterparts and friends, a draft of the new Constitution.
And his mission is fulfilled, as 64% of voters, according to official results covering 80% of the votes, voted in the referendum "yes".
According to these results, 28% of the votes were invalid and 0.7% of the ballots were empty.
In order for the bill to be adopted, he had to get half the vote plus one.
Two polls conducted in the east of the polling room and a calculation by NGOs predicted a clear "yes" victory on Sunday, situating them in the range of 63% to 70%.
Rafael Correa demanded the victory of his draft constitution on Sunday night.
"The constitution has won on the whole line," he assured and congratulated Ecuadorians at Guayaquil Governorate headquarters, 280 kilometers southwest of Quito.
It goes without saying that Rafael Correa received greetings from Chávez and Morales, but also from his Chilean counterpart, Michelle Bachelet.
The vote, which, according to the Organization of American States (OAS) observation mission, took place quietly, concerned the text on 444 points building “new socialism” promoted by the president.
The draft Constitution consecrates the power of the state over the economy by reserving to it the “development planning” of a country that lives primarily from the extraction of oil by foreign companies and from the currencies sent by its emigrants.
The proposal, protected by Correa, which was elected in 2006, also extends the powers of the head of state, who will be able to exercise two consecutive four-year mandates and be able to dissolve the House.
Correa has already announced that he will exercise this power and will apply for a new mandate in February 2009.
Among other things, the constitution upholds the principle of free health and education, which the president began to introduce in a country with 13.9 million inhabitants, where 50% of the population lives below the poverty line.
Finally, it also plans to ban the presence of foreign troops, terminating the agreement between Washington and Quito to use the Ecuadorian base as a starting point for U.S. anti-drug operations.
19 hostages freed in Chad
The Egyptian commando attacked the kidnapper of eleven tourists and their eight-member escort, who were captured ten days ago.
They're in Cairo.
Eleven European tourists and their eight Egyptian guides, who were held captive in the desert for ten days, were transported alive and well to the Egyptian capital on Monday.
During the morning, an Egyptian commando was liberated in Chad.
The hostages flew around 3:30 p.m., apparently in good shape, aboard a special jet to al-Maza military base, close to the Cairo International Airport.
They were immediately transported, without having the opportunity to express themselves in the press, aboard a helicopter to a hospital in Maadi, the outskirts of Cairo’s residential district, to undergo medical examinations there.
"They are completely healthy" and "no ransom has been paid to the kidnappers," Egypt's tourism minister Zohejr Garrana said on the airport's runway.
Since its capture on September 19, during a safari in a four-wheel drive vehicle at the foot of Mount Uanat, on the borders of Egypt, Sudan and Libya, a group of hostages has been dragged from one hideout to another by 35 unknown kidnappers.
The group includes 11 tourists – five Italians, five Germans and one Romanian – as well as eight Egyptians: two guides, four drivers, one border director of the Aegyptous agency, organizers of safaris.
A senior Egyptian security official suggested that 30 members of special forces who approached the site on board two helicopters set off on a leak during the night just before dawn.
"There was a shooting, half of the kidnappers were killed and the others fled," the source, who wished to remain anonymous, said.
He indicated that a total of 150 members of the Egyptian special forces from the “lightning” unit were sent to Sudan, where they gained the support of German and Italian commandos.
The head of Italian diplomacy, Franco Frattini, mentioned the role played by secret agents and members of the Italian special forces from Belgrade, where he is currently based.
"We have to acknowledge that we have achieved this result thanks to the professionalism and efficiency of the people from our secret services, from the special forces," he said.
He also denied that the ransom would be paid.
On the eve of the attack, the Sudanese army said it had detained a four-wheel-drive vehicle on board the hijackers, killing six of them, including a Chadian commander, and arresting two.
The army claimed they were affiliated with a group of rebels in Darfur, the Sudan Liberation Movement - Unity (SLA-U), which the movement immediately rejected.
