The fox in the chicken coop
Life and health insurance companies in America often deny the possibility of concluding an insurance contract with an applicant based on people’s data on the purchase of medicines.
Data protection experts fear that the data market will become uncontrollable.
"There is a data protection program that binds the use of prescription drug data in any case to the consent of the person concerned.
It must be in the hands of someone independent, otherwise we entrust the henhouse to the fox," Richard Dick, the author of the program for monitoring prescription drugs, told the Washington Post.
Insurance companies make insurance and the amounts paid in the event of insurance events depend on the health status of the applicants, and if the risk is assessed as too high, they do not even close insurance with it.
They had previously sent the persons concerned for medical examinations and only concluded the contract when they knew their results.
Ten years ago, Dick invented a much cheaper procedure: based on an identification number from pharmacies, a customer can easily find out what medications the person has bought in the last year and a half, from which the program itself deduces what type of disease he suffers from and what his health condition is.
For example, if you regularly buy large amounts of cholesterol-lowering drugs, this refers to the fact that you have virtually uncontrollably high blood fat levels, which immediately puts you in the category of at-risk.
There are several versions of the program in circulation, some also determine the risk factor at the same time, so that the insurance company has almost no work left besides paperwork, although minor problems arise.
The disadvantages include that leckter drugs can also be used for several purposes, some compounds are useful, for example, against migraines or hot flashes, but they are also effective against depression.
These represent a significant risk-increasing factor from the point of view of commercial insurance companies, whereas the first mentioned difficulties do not.
In order to request and process data, special companies have been created, which, before providing the necessary information from pharmacies, ask the patient for permission.
The authorities are now forcing them to do so, although they have not been punished for their past negligence.
Recently, some companies have also been processing the results of laboratory tests, which are linked to data on the medicines they are taking, which allows them to provide an even more accurate picture of the health of patients.
More and more companies have access to data, at the same time it will be increasingly difficult to control their use.
There is a special law on the protection of health data, but its effectiveness applies only to health service providers and insurance companies.
The bill, which will give authorities the power to control even companies specializing in providing data, is before Congress.
Richard Dick acknowledges that this is not enough: therefore, he developed his program in such a way that the transfer of data is subject to the explicit consent of the person concerned.
Another thing is that he can barely refuse the permission in question, otherwise insurance companies will not conclude a contract with him.
So the chickens are just a little tied to the boa will line.
