EU and India to double trade turnover
As the European Union and India are each other's leading trading partners, this theme led the agenda of the ninth summit, among other, mostly global issues.
Today there will also be a Franco-Indian summit, which will focus on cooperation in the field of nuclear energy.
The European Union recognises that India is an emerging democratic power, which should be given greater opportunity to speak on international issues, but Member States have not yet been able to find a common denominator in support of the permanent membership of New Delhi in the UN Security Council.
This issue was thus not further discussed at yesterday's, already ninth summit, held in Marseille.
French President Nicolas Sarkozy, as the current President of the Union, and European Commission President José Manuel Barroso, respectively, and High Representative for Foreign Affairs Javier Solana welcomed Indian Prime Minister Manmohan Singh, with whom they also agreed that the turnover of trade in five years will double, or increase to more than one billion euros.
Since the trade in goods rose from 25 billion to 55 billion between 2000 and 2007, this is not an overly ambitious target.
Twenty-six existing bilateral agreements on civil aviation with India have been legally reconciled, giving the green light to future air transport.
By the end of 2009, India would like to sign a free trade agreement with the Union.
Sarkozy said the talks would be accelerated.
The aim is to balance the balance, while the EU is India’s first trading partner, New Delhi ranks among the EU’s partners up to ninth.
The summit also paid attention to global issues.
The situation in Afghanistan and Pakistan, or terrorism, respectively, both sides condemned it in all its forms and called for an accelerated convening of the UN conference.
They also urged the conclusion of the Doha round of trade talks, although both have a large share in its previous failure.
The European Union has confirmed that it will insist on its energy and climate agenda, namely that it would like to reduce emissions of harmful substances by at least twenty percent by 2020.
India also agreed to this, as well as to the need to conclude a global agreement at next year’s climate conference and reduce greenhouse gas production by 50 percent by 2050.
Both sides would also like to prevent rising food prices and support the convening of an international conference to address the financial crisis.
The Prime Minister of India is on a visit to the French capital today, where he is about to conclude a deal on the peaceful use of nuclear energy at a bilateral meeting.
Paris believes that commissions for the construction of Indian nuclear reactors worth twenty billion euros will be received by French companies.
According to agency reports, the agreement should be valid for 15 years.
